AUDIO: 'are here at Cine Gear 2026 in Los Angeles and I\'m with Nick from Tilta. How\'s it going, man? &gt;&gt; Doing pretty good. How you doing? &gt;&gt; Doing good. I feel like we just saw each other. &gt;&gt; Yeah, I know. It is a pretty small gap between &gt;&gt; [laughter]'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; N D and Cine Gear. &gt;&gt; Yes. And but, you know, Tilta always has something new to share with us. So, what do we got here? &gt;&gt; So, these are the Illusion Magnetic Filter System. These are essentially modular filters that double as polarizers, variable N D filters,'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'diffusion. The idea is you screw on an adapter to lenses up to 86 mm and then these filters just kind of drop on. So, whether it\'s as simple as just a polarizer filter or you want to turn that polarizer into a VND, you have some'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'options in a in a lightweight package. &gt;&gt; So, there is magnetic. &gt;&gt; Yeah. Yeah, so it\'s magnetic to the adapter. So, it does let you rotate once it\'s on. So, if you\'re just polarizing, circular polarizer, completely fine. Snap on that VND adapter. Each piece can'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lock into the piece before it. So, there are these alignment notches. Meaning, if you want to throw on one of the filters and have it completely static, you you can lock that in place but then you also can very easily adjust it so it doesn\'t'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spin. You can kind of build the filter you need. Different kinds of polarizers, some with ND. So, if you\'re shooting outside like right now where it\'s pretty bright and sunny, you can already start with some additional stops of ND so your'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'VND doesn\'t have as much to travel or if you need a little bit of diffusion, you know, some black mist is in a different polarizer and and yeah, the idea is these kind of all are lightweight, fairly inexpensive. &gt;&gt; They\'re very lightweight.'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; They they pack up into a nice little, you know, compact little uh &gt;&gt; Little carrying case. &gt;&gt; Yeah, well &gt;&gt; [laughter] &gt;&gt; Now, does it have a stop on it so that it doesn\'t you don\'t get the the X? &gt;&gt; Yeah. Yeah, so if if you\'re holding this guy, you can see we have these alignment'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'notches right here. And then every filter, including the adapter rings, has an alignment notch. So if I line it up with that notch, you can see I missed it cuz it\'s spinning, but all I got to do is find it, get over it, lock, and then &gt;&gt; Okay.'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; So that\'s how you would build your VND, lock your polarizer, put the VND adapter over, and then that takes the polarizer element and then makes it &gt;&gt; Turns it into a VND. All right, that\'s cool. So you can use it as a polarizer, or you could throw a'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one of these little filters in and then you can have an adjustable VND. &gt;&gt; We also have a UV filter. We have adapters for some of the old 95 mm circular filter. So anyone who already has kind of purchased into that ecosystem can still use this new magnetic, you know, connection. And'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yeah, just, you know, an easy way to get some some filters in front of your lens. I think a lot of people who are using the original Mirage really like just having that VND on the lens and didn\'t always need the full-size matte box. So this is kind of a response to that and'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of making it as slim as possible. &gt;&gt; So how many different how many filters do we have in a in a set, or are you just buy individual &gt;&gt; So we do have a few we do have a few different kits. The kind of main kit is'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to come with four filters. So it\'s three different polarizer filters and then one VND adapter that can be used with any of the polarizers. So one normal polarizer, one polarizer with five stops of ND, and then one polarizer'

